,Recommended,287600,16752558,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,The Dainty Cossack,"A beautiful game that will put you in the main character's skin more tangibly than most games i've played. Beautiful story, original mechanics (being a housekeeper/bystander during a revolution) and interesting message.The game really shines in its atmosphere. You'll arrive each day before sunset to clean the apartment and the apartment would naturally evolve, like any apartment after a week. You'll grow to really love that apartment. Know its rooms, its nooks and crannies. You'll get to know your employer and his habits, his interests and concerns. The story will really begin when he'll leave you your first note thanking you for your hard work. You spent most of the game alone in that apartment eager to read his notes to find out what he wants to tell you or what he was thinking.I admit, the social justice themes get old after a few hours into the game. Yeah, war is bad, we get it, but it gets really stale. Luckily, you can avoid all that by avoiding writing the diary. I think the criticism this game has been getting is unfair - the game is quite good.The story is disjointed at times though... some things don't make any sense and will leave your head scratching. Clearly written by amateurs. Nonetheless, it's a better story than a close equivalent Gone Home for example.Overall, it's definitely worth it if you're looking for a different game like Gone Home and are interested in some social justice/anti war monologues."
,Recommended,287600,16860529,"Posted: 3 July, 2015",all,Hypnotoad,"There are brief moments of clarity, insight, and humanity in this that mark the experience as worthwhile. The game is smart (as in, smartly written, and almost spare in its approach to interaction) but it doesn't bludgeon you around the head with its erudition (I'm looking at you, Talos Principle...)There are very clear nods to ideas and discussions that someone with an elaborately useless fine arts / humanties background would appreciate. And there are games that are played with the interface and the ideas of video-game conventions - the checklist, the arbitrary timer, the old modus of hunt-click-interact that we've been trained on since we were tiny little half-formed gamesters flinging cursors around the pocket-pixels of old Lucas-Arts adventures.But it never rubs your face in it. There's a set of simple tasks, and then those that are hidden - implied. Big questions, that might not gel with your own politics. Hey - what of it? Play through the character. Try to get inside her head - work through this little fragmentary window - filtered through genre conventions and cliche and bias...If we only watched the films that made us comfortable - if we only read literature we agreed with - we'd be lesser for it. Same for games.This is a worthwhile game. This is... interesting... despite its flaws. And it's... engrossing. It took about four hours of my evening without my even realising - just flicking through - day to day."
