,Recommended,287600,15978159,"Posted: 23 May, 2015",all,lake.kubilius,"Sunset is a fascinating and unique game of a type I wish we saw more of.  It's very much like reading a novel; I'd say it's one of the most elegant attempts at making a game be a novel that I've ever seen.The graphics are fantastic.  As some have noted, performance can seem unexpectedly poor on a low end computer (reminiscent of ""Tex Murphy: Overseer"" back in the day, for me, on my weaker machine).  But on my newer system, the graphics are flawlessly smooth, delectably stylized, and I can't imagine wanting to change a thing.The game is unusual in that it seems a bit as if you can do your job as poorly or disinterestedly as you please with absolutely no negative feedback.  This is unusual, and takes a bit of getting used to.  Eventually, the story begins to offer a plausible explanation for why this might be, but I didn't trust this concept for a good while.  I plan on doing a second playthrough shortly to test the theory that I am completely free to sociopathically disregard the work I am (theoretically) being paid to do at all times.  The game mechanics suggest that this is really how I was meant to be playing the game all along in the first place.Really the only negative thing I have to say is that I have a suspicion that a few of the Steam Achievements might be buggy.  I definitely saw things that would make me assume I should have a few more of them than I do, and all of the ones I think that about show 0% of players successful.  Hopefully a patch will clear that up in the near future."
