76561198003261964,Recommended,287600,15985588,"Posted: 24 May, 2015",all,BoiledHippo,"Like all other games by Tale of Tales, Sunset is a visually striking as it is interesting and engaging to play. This game stands apart from previous ToT games, however, in that is a less abstract, more filled out game, with a storyline that is not left almost entirely up to the player (see The Path, Bientot L'ete, or Salome). It is still a game very much in the ToT style, however. The amount of detail in the apartmetn, the ever-shifting light and ever-changing setting, is absolutely stunning.I will agree with other comments about performance issues, but it's not enough to keep me from enjoying the game, or from being totally swept up in the beautiful story of Angela and Gabriel.Tale of Tales has always been my standard for the ""not-games"" or ""visual novel"" genre of gaming. There is no combat,  no puzzles, but there are choices the player makes that determine the outcome of events both within the apartment and in the entire country.Sunset is a beautiful, engaging piece of art that you can explore, caress, strike down, or discover. I cannot recommend it highly enough."
,Recommended,287600,16240008,"Posted: 7 June, 2015",all,castorquinn,"In BriefSunsetis a unique, profound narrative game about art, and people, and it made me fall in love.Most valuable resource:The unique, incredibly well thought-out use of gameplay.Of interest to:people interested in character, relationships, philosophy, and art.Tale of Taleshave a history of very cleverly using gameplay elements to construct an experience.  These are the same people who madeThe Path, which messed with your expectations about player choice, and game advancement, andBientot L'ete, a multiplayer game about loneliness.  WithSunsetthough they have excelled themselves.It's the 1970s, and you are a black American who left her homeland for the Latin American nation of Anchuria for personal reasons, and now finds herself, engineering degree and all, working as a maid for a rich member of the ruling elite.  Gameplay is very straightforward: once a week you arrive at his house, receive a list of chores, and have an hour to do them.  Although you're on the clock, the game doesn't feel like a time trial; it's more about making choices.  The game is repetitive, but in a completely engaging way; each day is the same house, the same basic routine, with different chores, but very quickly that stops being the point as you slowly learn more about the man you are working for, a man you've never met but whose house you routinely occupy.Against a backdrop of a military dictatorship, the game has a lot to say about progress and tradition, about art, and people, and war.  It uses religion, and art, and music as its motifs, and the diary entries and commentary of this person as whom you play is subtle, and gentle, tangential to the points the game is making, letting you think about it, think it through.  A lot of art games that have something to say jam it down your throat, butSunsetis happy to just talk, just show you things, and let you experience people, and then think about it and see to what conclusions you come yourself.  Because it isn't forcing the issue the game can be quite high-brow without pushing people away with pretension.There are collectibles in the form of a selection of literature that pertains to the issues raised during the game, and obscure music discs.  The collectibles hint at some of the ideas in the story, but they also make you feel like the house you clean is occupied by someone else; you get to know him a little by his books, which is, again, such a subtle thing.  That he leaves these books and records out at times feels deliberate, like he wants you to see what he is reading for some reason, to share in his music, building a strangely, unexpectedly strong connection between you and this person you've not yet met.  This game could easily feel sterile, with its modern house and its simplicity of location, but instead these little touches make the experience instead feel intimate.The game has one hundred achievements.  I don't believe the developers did this without thought.  For me, at least, finishing the game with 71 achievements made me feel like I still didn't fully know Ortega, which, given how the story progresses, is quite a profound way to end.  If this was the intention then these developers are artists who paid great attention to every detail of the gaming experience.There is so much more to say about this game, but I want to avoid spoiling anything you may take from the game through your own experience of playing it.  If this sort of narrative experience sounds like something you might enjoy, take a punt and playSunset.  All art is subjective, but for me, there is every chance that this delicately crafted story will be my game of the year."
